775-a268-fecf4708f133` — master orchestrator subagent — done ✅\n12. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:b653a6c0-143b-4b53-a242-034bc5fd9fca` — orphaned cron — orphaned ❌\n13. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:ac986a8d-2425-40c7-835b-ed9b101b0bff` — another orphaned cron — orphaned ❌\n\nMost of the subagents and scheduled jobs have completed, though there are a couple of orphaned cron jobs that need attention.\n\nLooking at the DTLX 5p Monitor run at 04:02 UTC, I'm seeing a shift in the session landscape. The QLHV and DTLX monitoring sessions are still active, but the Agent Status cron has dropped off. Meanwhile, the Lead direct session is back online with six child subagents, and the QLHV Telegram group is running again.\n\nComparing the current state at 04:09 UTC to that 04:02 snapshot, I notice the DTLX 5p cron is still churning with three active planner children, the DTLX Telegram group remains failed, and the Agent Status cron hasn't reappeared. The main session and QLHV Telegram group are both still running. The real question is whether anything material has actually changed—the Agent Status session disappearing and the Lead direct coming back online are notable, but I need to figure out if these represent genuine state shifts or just noise in the monitoring cycle.\n\nLooking at the timing more carefully, the Lead direct session last showed activity at 03:49 UTC, which was about 20 minutes before the 04:02 report, but this current cron run at 04:09 UTC is seeing updatedAt timestamps that are even more stale—the Lead direct hasn't actually changed since before 03:49, and the QLHV group hasn't budged since 03:18 UTC. So the active sessions at 04:09 are still just the QLHV 5p monitor, the DTLX 5p monitor, and the QLHV group, with everything else in a holding pattern.\n\nNow I'm checking what the DTLX 5p cron actually did at 04:02—it reported that the Agent Status cron was gone, the main session had ended normally around 03:25, and the Lead direct was still running with